Preheat your oven to 200°C. Quarter the @Salad Potatoes{350%g} (no need to peel). Using a #peeler{}, peel the @Mango{1} then stand it upright on your #chopping board{}. Slice down either side of the stone to give you 2 'cheeks'. Slice any remaining flesh from the stone, then chop the mango into 1cm pieces. Discard the stone.

Pop the potatoes on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with @olive oil{1%tbsp}, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your #oven{} until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

While the potatoes cook, halve the @Baby Plum Tomatoes{125} and pop them in a large #bowl{} and set aside. Trim and thinly slice the @Spring Onion{1}. Zest and halve the @Lime{1}. Finely chop the @Coriander{1%bunch} (stalks and all). Halve the @Red Chilli{½}(deseeded) lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Pour the @Honey{15%g}, squeeze in the lime juice and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Mix together. Put the mango, spring onion, chilli (add less if you don't like spice) and coriander in the bowl and mix everything together.

> You also need @?olive oil{1%tbsp} (use the ingredient in the ingredient list for amount).

Spoon two thirds of the mango salsa into the tomatoes - mix again and set aside. Pop the lime zest in a small bowl and add the oil. Season with salt and pepper and mix together. Put the @Sea Bream Fillets{2} onto a #plate{}. Spoon equal quantities of the lime mixture onto each. Spread the mixture all over the bream so the fillets are evenly coated.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling the raw fish.

When the potatoes have 10 minutes left in the oven. Heat a #frying pan{} on medium high heat (no oil). Once hot, carefully place your bream in the pan, skin side down and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} before turning over and cooking for ~{2-3%minutes} on the other side.

> Tip: In order to get crispy skin on the fish, don't move it around when it's cooking skin side down!

Remove the pan from the heat.

> IMPORTANT: The bream is cooked when opaque all the way through.

Add the @Pea Shoots{40%g} to the mango and tomato mixture and toss to coat. Place a bream fillet on your plates and add the roast potatoes alongside. Serve the peashoot salad on the side. Spoon the remaining mango salsa on top of the bream. Enjoy.